'''Unebiyamaguchi Shrine''' (うねびやまぐちじんじゃ, おむねやまじんじゃ<ref name="a">On the signboard in front of the Mt. Unebi trailhead by the shrine, “畝火山口” is given the reading “おむねやま”.</ref>) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} on the western foot of {{ill|lt=Mount Unebi|Q17606448|WD=Q17606448|1=Mount Unebi}} in {{ill|lt=Kashihara|Q496319|WD=Q496319|1=Kashihara, Nara}}, {{ill|lt=Nara Prefecture|Q131287|WD=Q131287|1=Nara Prefecture}}. It is popularly called “Omine-yama.” It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}, and its former {{ill|lt=shrine rank|Q10444029|WD=Q10444029|1=Shakaku}} was prefectural shrine.

It is one of the six Yamaguchi shrines in Yamato listed in the norito of the {{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}} ({{ill|lt=Asuka Shrine#Precincts|Q11665959|WD=Q11665959|lt=Asuka|1=Asuka-ni-Imasu Shrine}}, Ishimura, Osa, Hase, '''Unebi''', and {{ill|lt=Miminashi Yamaguchi Shrine|Q11610732|WD=Q11610732|lt=Miminashi|1=Miminashi Yamaguchi Shrine}}), and one of the 85 shrines of the rain-prayer rites in the {{ill|lt=special festivals|Q11612499|WD=Q11612499|1=special festivals}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
It enshrines Okinagatarashihime-no-Mikoto ({{ill|lt=Empress Jingū|Q232803|WD=Q232803|1=Empress Jingū}}), {{ill|lt=Toyouke-hime|Q2983724|WD=Q2983724|lt=Toyouke-hime-no-Mikoto|1=Toyouke-hime}}, and {{ill|lt=Sumiyoshi three deities|Q1114013|WD=Q1114013|lt=Uwatsutsuo-no-Mikoto|1=Sumiyoshi sanjin}}. Based on the tradition that Empress Jingū gave birth to Emperor Ōjin, it is worshiped as a deity of safe childbirth.

From examples of other {{ill|lt=Yamaguchi shrines|Q11467399|WD=Q11467399|1=Yamaguchi shrines}} and the shrine’s character, the original deity is thought to have been {{ill|WD=Q386563|lt=Ōyamatsumi|Q386563|WD=Q386563|WD=Q386563|lt=Ōyamatsumi-no-Mikoto|1=Ōyamatsumi}}. Today Ōyamatsumi-no-Mikoto is enshrined in the auxiliary Ōyamatsumi Shrine.

=== History ===
The origin of the foundation is unknown. The first documentary appearance is in ''Shinshō Kakuchokufu-shō'', which records one shrine household granted in {{ill|lt=806|Q30021|WD=Q30021|1=806}} ({{ill|lt=Daidō|Q1373191|WD=Q1373191|1=Daidō}} 1). According to ''{{ill|lt=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|Q1052981|WD=Q1052981|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}}'', in {{ill|lt=859|Q23897|WD=Q23897|1=859}} ({{ill|lt=Jōgan|Q1075635|WD=Q1075635|1=Jōgan}} 1), on {{ill|lt=January 27 (lunar)|Q839032|WD=Q839032|lt=1st month 27th day|1=January 27 (Lunisolar)}}, it received {{ill|lt=court rank for shrines|Q11591025|WD=Q11591025|1=Shinkai (divine rank)}} of Senior Fifth Lower, and on {{ill|lt=September 8 (lunar)|Q840354|WD=Q840354|lt=September 8|1=September 8 (Lunisolar)}} of the same year an {{ill|lt=imperial envoy with offerings|Q11445508|WD=Q11445508|1=Hōhei}} was dispatched for {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=rain prayer|1=UNKNOWN}}. In the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} it appears as “Unebi Yamaguchi-za Shrine, Takachi District, Yamato Province,” is listed as a great shrine, and is recorded as receiving offerings at monthly and Niiname rites.

Originally it stood on the western foot of Mt. Unebi. In the ''Gogun Jinjaki'' of {{ill|lt=Bun'an|Q1193586|WD=Q1193586|1=Bun'an}} 3 ({{ill|lt=1446|Q6430|WD=Q6430|1=1446}}), it is described as “at Kume-gō, western mountain tail of Mt. Unebi.” But maps of the {{ill|lt=Tenshō|Q1145058|WD=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} era place it on the summit, meaning it was moved from the foot to the summit between Bun'an and Tenshō. The shrine name evolved from Unebi-za Yamaguchi Shrine; in the Edo period it was also called “Unebi Myōjin” and “Unebi-yama Jingū-sha.”

In {{ill|lt=1940|Q18633|WD=Q18633|1=1940}} ({{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|WD=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 15), when major expansion works were carried out at {{ill|lt=Kashihara Jingū|Q710333|WD=Q710333|1=Kashihara Shrine}} on the eastern foot of Mt. Unebi, it was deemed, in the climate of the high tide of {{ill|lt=imperial-state historiography|Q5368837|WD=Q5368837|1=Kōkoku shikan}}, that looking down over Kashihara Jingū and Emperor Jinmu’s mausoleum would “defile divine authority”<ref>According to the explanatory notice at the torii of Unebiyamaguchi Shrine.</ref>. The Japanese government therefore ordered relocation to the western foot (current site). At that time it was promoted from {{ill|lt=gōsha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}} to prefectural shrine.

=== Rituals ===
A special ritual called “Hani-tsuchi ritual” is held. It takes soil from the summit of Mt. Unebi for making earthenware used at {{ill|lt=Sumiyoshi Taisha|Q705949|WD=Q705949|1=Sumiyoshi-taisha}} in the {{ill|lt=Kinen-sai|Q118906710|WD=Q118906710|1=Kinensai}} (February) and {{ill|lt=Niiname-sai|Q11501518|WD=Q11501518|1=Niiname-no-Matsuri}} (November). On that occasion, those performing the rite customarily prepare their ritual garments at {{ill|lt=Kawamata Shrine|Q11553360|WD=Q11553360|1=Kawamata Shrine (Q11553360)}} before heading to this shrine.

